channel.description:
Once we’ve built a website that can send form data using an HTTP POST request to our web application, we need some way to access that information in our controller. Let’s look at how we would accomplish this in Flask.
Flask Path Variables In a previous example, we saw how we can create a route that includes variables directly in the path itself:
@route('/greeting/<name>/') def greeting_with_name(self, name): """Display greeting with name.""" return render_template("greeting.html", name=name) In this example, we simply include the path variable <name in the route, and a corresponding parameter in our controller function. Flask will automatically match the name of that parameter to the name of one of the path variables in the route, and fill in the value when it calls the function.
